    <h1>Taj Mahal</h1>
    <div class="about"><p>The Taj Mahal is a world-renowned white marble mausoleum located in Agra, India, on the banks of the Yamuna River. It was commissioned by the Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan in 1631 as a tribute to his beloved wife, Mumtaz Mahal, who died during childbirth. The Taj Mahal stands as a symbol of eternal love and is one of the most famous architectural masterpieces in the world.

        The construction of the Taj Mahal began in 1632 and was completed in 1653, employing thousands of workers, artisans, and craftsmen from across the empire. The monument combines elements of Persian, Ottoman Turkish, and Indian architectural styles, featuring a grand dome, intricate carvings, and lush gardens. The central structure houses the tombs of Shah Jahan and Mumtaz Mahal.
        
        The Taj Mahal is made primarily of white marble, which changes color depending on the time of day, from soft pink in the morning to golden in the evening. The surrounding complex includes a mosque, a guest house, and a reflecting pool that enhances the visual symmetry of the design.
        
        In 1983, the Taj Mahal was designated a **UNESCO World Heritage Site** and is also considered one of the New Seven Wonders of the World. It attracts millions of visitors annually, celebrated for its beauty, craftsmanship, and the poignant love story behind its creation.</p></div>
